    "contenu": "### The Categories of Languedoc-Roussillon Wine\n\n#### Wine Labeling in France\n- **Appellation System**: In French wine regions, wines are typically labeled by the appellation from which they originate, rather than the grape variety. Examples include Sancerre and Saint-Émilion.\n- **Appellation d’Origine Contrôlée (AOC)**: Up until 2009, this was the standard for strict regional wine-making regulations in France.\n- **Protected Designation of Origin (PDO)**: Post-2009, French appellations can also utilize this European Union designation, expanding the regulatory framework.\n\n#### Appellation Wines in Languedoc-Roussillon\n- **Purpose**: These wines aim to reflect their terroir and origin.\n- **Examples of Appellation Wines**:\n  - Corbières\n  - Faugères\n  - Minervois\n- These wines are noted for being particularly reflective of their specific areas within Languedoc-Roussillon.\n- **Outstanding Appellations Mentioned**:\n  - Corbières-Boutenac\n  - Minervois La Livinière\n  - Saint-Chinian Roquebrun\n  - Saint-Chinian Berlou\n- Additional crus in the region are pending official approval.\n\n#### Vin de Pays d’Oc\n- **Variety-Based Labeling**: Unlike appellation wines, Vin de Pays d’Oc is labeled based on the grape variety such as chardonnay or merlot. \n- **Geographical Source**: These wines can be sourced from anywhere within the Languedoc-Roussillon region, which may or may not reflect a specific locality’s characteristics.\n- **Notable Example**: Mas de Daumas Gassac, renowned particularly for its red wine made primarily from cabernet sauvignon, rivaling the quality of top Bordeaux wines.\n- **Pop Culture Reference**: Mas de Daumas Gassac gained prominence after being featured in the wine film \"Mondovino\".\n\n#### Conclusion\nLanguedoc-Roussillon offers a complex and richly varied wine landscape, marked by both traditional appellations reflecting deep terroir and modern, flexible wines labeled by grape variety, catering to diverse tastes and preferences."
