    "source": "inconnu_544",
    "contenu": "The document discusses the science of thickening sauces using molecules, specifically discussing clear dispersions, gels, and solid dispersions. Below is an organized breakdown of the text:\n\n### 1. Clear Dispersions and Gels: Thickening with Molecules\n- **Introduction**: A single microscopic fragment of a tomato cell wall or muscle fiber consists of many submicroscopic molecules.\n- **Properties**:\n  - These molecules are large and built up from many small fragments.\n  - They can be teased away from each other and remain dispersed in water, without settling or separating.\n  - Common thickening agents include starch, pectins, and certain proteins like gelatin.\n- **Characteristics**:\n  - These agents are effective because they are smaller and lighter than the entire starch granules and cell fragments they originate from.\n  - They do not settle out and their small size and widespread distribution help in blocking light rays, giving them a translucent, glassy appearance.\n  - Longer molecules are generally more effective as thickening agents.\n\n### 2. Solid Dispersions: Jellies\n- **Description**: When water in a food fluid contains enough thickening molecules and is undisturbed during cooling, it forms a network where the molecules become immobile, thickening the fluid.\n- **Properties**:\n  - This network formation allows the fluid to become a moist solid or gel, which can be very wobbly, comprising mostly water (up to 99%) with a minimal amount (about 1%) of gelatin.\n  - If made from dissolved molecules, the gel appears translucent.\n\n### Illustrations\nThe document includes illustrations comparing the molecular structure of starch and gelatin:\n- **Starch Molecules**: Show tangled, interconnected lines representing how starch molecules entangle and obstruct the flow of liquid.\n- **Gelatin Molecules**: Depict more relaxed and wave-like structures, indicating a more flexible entanglement compared to starch.\n\n### Summary Caption\n- **Caption**:\n  \"Thickening a liquid with long food molecules. Dissolved molecules of plant starch or animal gelatin get tangled up with each other and impede the flow of the liquid.\"\n\nThis information provides a scientific perspective on how various food molecules behave differently when used as thickeners in cooking, affecting the texture and consistency of sauces and gels."
  },
