    "contenu": "Sure, here is the transcribed and structured content of your document:\n\n---\n\n## Clove & Orange\n*See Orange & Clove.*\n\n## Clove & Peach\nCertain rare fruits contain eugenol, the distinguishing flavor of cloves, and peach is one of them. This might explain why the recipe for marinated peaches studded with cloves is very popular in the southern United States. The peaches must be peeled before inserting the cloves. A delicate task indeed!\n\n## Clove & Apple\n*See Apple & Clove.*\n\n## Clove & Pork\nCloves and pork pair very well, not only for taste reasons but also because they act as natural preservatives. Eugenol found in cloves has a potent antioxidant effect that extends even to the fatty components of pork dishes. As consumers become increasingly wary of synthetic additives, we may soon see more partnerships like this — a trend that certainly wouldn't be unwelcome.\n\n## Clove & Tomato\n*See Tomato & Clove.*\n\n## Clove & Vanilla\n*See Vanilla & Clove.*\n\n## Nutmeg\n\nThe botanical name for nutmeg is *Myristica fragrans*, which fittingly sounds like the name of a James Bond girl, suggesting something exotic enough for a magnificent double agent. Nutmeg is less daunting and easier to break into desserts and cruciferous vegetables (cabbage, turnip, rutabaga). The mace, which covers the nutmeg seed, contains similar compounds but in different proportions and with fewer essential oils. Both are interchangeable but fresh presentations are generally preferred over pre-ground versions. Nutmeg is easier to grate than mace's delicate lace, and it's somewhat less bitter.\n\n### Nutmeg & Lamb\nBefore I learned to cook, I enjoyed spaghetti bolognese in a tavern in Corfu. The dish was delightful partly because the lamb had been minced and aromatized with sweet ground nutmeg. They had used nutmeg to perfect a pasta sauce made with half a liter of water, 1 tbsp of diced vegetable broth, 250 ml of white wine, and 2 tbsp of soup base. After incorporating 250 ml of meat sauce and 250 ml of vegetable stock, they seasoned with a pinch of nutmeg, simmered for an hour, and added a tablespoon of sugar to enhance the flavors. This example illustrates how even slight changes, like adding nutmeg, can provide long-lasting effects on classical dishes.\n\n### Nutmeg & Eggplant\n*See Eggplant & Nutmeg.*\n\n### Nutmeg & Avocado\nIt is said that avocado mixed with nutmeg can have an aphrodisiac effect on men, largely because of vitamin B6, believed to stimulate testosterone production. Nutmeg allures people from all backgrounds — from boys stepping out in their first suits to men at sophisticated dinner parties. For an unforgettable treat, try blending nutmeg into chilled avocado soup or stuffing avocados with fruit and topping them with sprinkles of nutmeg.\n\n---"
