    "contenu": "The document provides insights into the use of wine in cooking, organized into advice and facts about using wine effectively:\n\n1. **If a Wine Tastes Bad, Don’t Cook With It**\n   - Bad wine will not improve by cooking as the unpleasant tastes like mildew or cork taint will remain. It is better to use wine that simply tastes faded or flattened for cooking, but not the ones with strong off odors.\n\n2. **If a Wine Tastes Very Good, Don’t Cook With It**\n   - Cooking with high-quality wine is considered a waste since the nuanced flavors and aromas are better appreciated when the wine is consumed directly. Exceptional wines will retain their taste even after opening and might still taste better the next day.\n\n3. **Cooking Reduces Wine, Concentrating Flavor and Removing Alcohol**\n   - When wine is cooked, alcohol and water evaporate which concentrates its flavors. This can enhance the remaining liquid in a dish, making flavor profiles like sweetness, fruitiness, or herb-like qualities more intense. However, a trace of alcohol remains regardless of cooking duration.\n\n4. **Wine Marinades Keep Fish Moist and Tenderize Meats**\n   - Wine serves as an effective marinade, helping to moisturize fish which tends to dry out quickly when cooked, and tenderizing meats. The acidity in wine acts like lemon or vinegar, which can enhance flavors and soften the meat’s texture through chemical reactions during marination."
