    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_58",
    "contenu": "The document discusses various aspects of the handling, storage, serving, and fermentation process of milk and dairy products, particularly focusing on ice cream and fresh fermented milks and creams.\n\n### Milk and Dairy Products\n\n#### Ice Cream\n\n1. **Mixing and Cooling:**\n   - The mix should be stirred to expose it to cold surfaces, incorporate some air, and produce a smooth texture.\n   - Slow cooling (especially if un-stirred) causes large, relatively few ice crystals that cluster into a coarse texture.\n   - Rapid cooling with stirring prevents large crystal growth and results in a smoother texture.\n\n2. **Hardening:**\n   - Occurs when the mix is mostly frozen and is the last stage of making ice cream.\n   - Hardening should be controlled to allow around 40% of water content to remain unfrozen, increasing the creamy texture.\n   - Hardening efficiency can be increased by dividing ice cream into smaller containers for a faster temperature drop.\n\n3. **Storage and Serving:**\n   - Ice cream is best stored as cold as possible at or below 0°F (–18°C) to maintain texture.\n   - Repeated freeze-thaw cycles during storage can cause ice crystals to grow larger, impacting texture negatively.\n   - During storage, ice cream absorbs odors and might get damaged or turn rancid if exposed to the air.\n\n#### Fresh Fermented Milks and Creams\n\n1. **Properties and Benefits:**\n   - Fermentation occurs spontaneously in milk, preserving it and adding nutritional and flavorful properties.\n   - Common products include yogurt and soured creams, which are popular due to their taste and health benefits.\n\n2. **Lactic Acid Bacteria:**\n   - These bacteria ferment the lactose in milk into lactic acid, which not only preserves milk but also contributes to its texture and flavor.\n   - Lactic acid bacteria are uniquely adapted to milk and are critical for various dairy products.\n\nThese sections highlight the scientific and practical approaches in dairy product preparation and storage, aiming to enhance both the safety and quality of these products."
  },
